{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.25,0.04,0.01,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113102"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95134"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4423"},{"type":"tags","id":"4424"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12206"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"},{"type":"tags","id":"12960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46657"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113102"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to a small rural GP obstetric unit in active labour at 40 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy which has been uncomplicated. The cardiotocograph shows reassuring features. On vaginal examination, she is 8 cm dilated with thick meconium-stained liquor draining. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne hour later she gives birth to a baby who is floppy and not breathing. The baby is moved to the Neonatal resuscitaire with heating and stimulated. However, the heart rate is 90 beats/min and the baby is still apnoeic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of the newborn?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive pressure ventilation","Endotracheal intubation and tracheal suctioning","Chest compressions","Intravenous adrenaline","Oropharyngeal and nasopharyngeal suctioning"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a newborn who has already received the initial steps of resuscitation (warming, drying, stimulation) but remains apnoeic with a heart rate below 100 beats/min. According to current neonatal resuscitation guidelines, the next step in this situation is to establish effective ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive pressure ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct next step for a newborn who remains apnoeic with a heart rate \u0026lt;100 beats/min after initial resuscitation steps. Effective ventilation is the most important intervention in neonatal resuscitation and should be established before proceeding to more invasive measures. For non-vigorous newborns born through meconium-stained amniotic fluid (those not breathing or crying with low muscle tone), current guidelines emphasise the importance of rapidly initiating ventilation rather than delaying to perform other interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation and tracheal suctioning\u003C/strong\u003E was previously recommended as the first step for non-vigorous newborns with meconium-stained liquor. However, current guidelines no longer recommend routine intubation for tracheal suctioning in this scenario, as studies have not shown it to improve outcomes. Intubation would be considered if bag-mask ventilation is ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest compressions\u003C/strong\u003E are only indicated if the heart rate remains below 60 beats/min despite 30 seconds of effective positive pressure ventilation. In this case, the heart rate is \u0026lt;100 but not specified as \u0026lt;60, so ventilation should be established first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is a later step in neonatal resuscitation, indicated only if the heart rate remains \u0026lt;60 beats/min despite effective ventilation and chest compressions. It would be premature to administer adrenaline at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOropharyngeal and nasopharyngeal suctioning\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the initial steps of resuscitation if there is obvious obstruction or if positive pressure ventilation requires suctioning to be effective. However, deep suctioning can cause vagal stimulation and delay ventilation, which is the priority in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current approach to meconium-stained liquor has evolved based on evidence. While meconium aspiration syndrome remains a concern, the focus has shifted to establishing effective ventilation promptly rather than performing procedures that may delay this critical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Current neonatal resuscitation guidelines recommend immediate positive pressure ventilation for newborns with heart rate \u003C100 and apnoea after initial steps.","Endotracheal intubation is no longer routinely recommended as the first intervention for non-vigorous newborns with meconium-stained liquor.","Effective ventilation is the priority in neonatal resuscitation, with chest compressions only indicated if heart rate remains \u003C60 despite adequate ventilation."],"references":["Australian and New Zealand Committee on Resuscitation (ANZCOR). Guideline 13.4: Airway management and mask ventilation of the newborn. ANZCOR; 2021. Available from: https://www.anzcor.org/assets/anzcor-guidelines/guideline-13-4-airway-management-and-mask-ventilation-of-the-newborn-288.pdf","NeoResus. Airway : First Response interventions. In: NeoResus [Internet]. Perth, Western Australia: NeoResus; circa 2022. Available at: https://www.neoresus.org.au/learning-resources/key-concepts/first-response/airway/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95134"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95134"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T15:05:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T15:07:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113102"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},